Eben Etzebeth is accused of hurling racial slurs at patrons at a pub in Langebaan. JOHANNESBURG - The South African Human Rights Commission has dropped its review application in the North Gauteng High Court against Springboks player, Eben Etzebeth. The two parties reached a mutual decision to rather have the matter heard by the Equality Court. Etzebeth is accused of racially insulting four patrons at a Langebaan pub on the West Coast last August. READ: Nienaber named new Bok coach The men who made the allegations are looking for more than R1-million in compensation. They also want Etzebeth to apologise and go for anger management and racial sensitivity training. Etzebeth, who was part of the 2019 rugby World Cup team, has denied the allegations.